# Delete, don't deprecate

When you remove or replace **anything** in this repo — routes, files, exports, APIs, types, env vars, config keys, DB fields, UI, feature flags, docs — **delete the old thing**. Do not leave compatibility layers, redirects, or “temporary” dual paths.

**Default:** one way to do it. The new way only.

## Never leave behind

- Redirect routes, URL aliases, or “old path → new path” handlers
- Re-exports or renamed aliases “for backwards compatibility”
- Wrapper functions that only forward to the replacement
- `@deprecated` symbols that still work
- Dual code paths (old + new) unless **both** are explicitly required in production *right now*
- Code paths for **states the new implementation never creates** (old enum values, old row shapes, old status fields) — e.g. handling `status === "confirmed"` after switching to delete-on-confirm
- Functions or symbols named `*Legacy*`, `*Old*`, `*Compat*`, or `*Migration*` in product code
- Commented-out old code “just in case”
- Feature flags gating the old implementation alongside the new one
- Stale docs, AGENTS.md, Storybook stories, or tests for removed behavior
- Empty folders, barrel files, or index re-exports pointing at deleted modules

## Behavior and data migrations

When behavior changes so the **new code never writes a state**, do **not** add handlers for that state “just in case.” Delete the branch. If old rows still exist in a deployment, that is a **one-time migration or manual cleanup** — not a permanent code path.

**Idempotency for the current design is allowed** — e.g. retry confirm after the staging row was already deleted, resolved via the new model (`captures.sourceScanId`, tag state, etc.).

**Idempotency for a superseded design is not allowed** — e.g. special-casing `status === "confirmed"` or `status === "aborted"` after the lifecycle switched to delete-on-terminal.

## When instructions conflict

If a plan, task, comment, or doc asks for backwards compatibility, legacy branches, or “keep handling old X,” **this rule wins** unless the user **explicitly overrides in the current conversation**.

Do not silently add migration shims because a plan mentions “legacy rows” or “existing behavior for old status.” Rewrite toward the new lifecycle only.

## Do instead

- Delete old and new in the **same change** (code, tests, docs, config)
- Grep the repo and fix **every** reference — not just the call site you touched
- If external consumers might break, say so in the PR — do **not** keep in-repo shims to hide it

## Examples

```tsx
// ❌ route shim
<Route path="/old" element={<Navigate to="/new" replace />} />

// ✅ old route gone
<Route path="new" element={<Screen />} />
```

```typescript
// ❌ alias export
export { newApi as oldApi };

// ✅ old name deleted; callers updated
export { newApi };
```

```typescript
// ❌ forwarding shim
export function startTagSession(...args) {
  return ensureNativeSession(...args);
}

// ✅ rename at all call sites; delete startTagSession
```

```typescript
// ❌ parallel implementations
if (useNewFlow) { … } else { …legacy… }

// ✅ legacy branch deleted after migration
```

```typescript
// ❌ handler for a terminal status the new flow never writes
if (scan.status === "confirmed") {
  return confirmLegacyScan(...);
}

// ✅ only states the new flow produces; missing row → current-model idempotency
if (scan.status !== "pending") {
  throw scanError(scanErrorCodes.scanNotPending);
}
// scan row gone → lookup captures.sourceScanId, not old status
```

Keeping two paths “for a smooth transition” inside this monorepo is **not** the default. A deliberate, time-boxed migration is a product/engineering decision — not something agents add silently.
